            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "While the situation has improved slightly in regards to Python 3, it's not really significant. \n\nAdoption is still very minimal and last time @mitsuhiko checked, I think we had more users on any single Python 2 release >= 2.6 including PyPy.\n\nIf you start using Python 3 now you are therefore still an early adopter with all the issues that brings. Furthermore even with the stdlib there are still significant issues in Python 3, click does a huge amount of work to deal with those and still runs better on 2.x. \n\nIn summary a recommendation for Python 3 will definitely not happen in the foreseeable future. \n"
        },
